        "content": "<p>There have been several times where I've tried to write something like this </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">myFileContent</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">File</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">writeBytes</span><span class=\"err\">!</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"/some/path\"</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>and been very surprised that I actually needed to write this</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">File</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">writeBytes</span><span class=\"err\">!</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"/some/path\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">myFileContent</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>In the <code>File</code> module my initial assumption is that the file content is the important data structure that is the first argument to the functions, not the file path. I frequently want to build up the file content in a pipeline, but never the path, so it seems very unergonomic.</p>\n<p>Because of this, I think we should change the file writing functions to accept the file content as the first argument. Thoughts?</p>",
        "id": 482887047,
        "sender_full_name": "Isaac Van Doren",
        "timestamp": 1731869675
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Absolutely a good idea, I've noticed the same thing</p>",
